<Author>Pochita
<Content>Nice, basic hostal I stayed at the Hostal Barrera with my husband and parents for 3 nights. The location is great, close to the Anton Martin metro station and the Atocha Renfe train station, as well as close to the two big museums the Prado and the Reina Sofia. I agree with some of the recent comments about the smell in the building- may be due to the old pipes or something, but it is something that we could tolerate. The front desk staff were very nice, very helpful- they own the hostal, and so are more invested than the average hotel worker. The bathrooms are VERY small- we are all fit folks, but anyone who is heavy or physically large will have some major problems using the bathroom/shower here. We banged our arms on the shower glass often when showering. We liked the security and the feeling that we had someone expecting us when we came in. The hotel is noisy- thin walls, echoing floors- so hope that your neighbors don't wear high heels (ours did), use hairdryers at night (ours did), or are heard of hearing (my dad is, and I'm sure everyone in the hostal heard what he had to say). And the trash folks don't worry about whether they are waking anyone up at 5:30 when they come down the street, so bring earplugs.The lift doesn't start at the bottom floor, so it was difficult for my older parents to carry their luggage up the half-flight (and thus hard for me and my husband to carry all our bags up the stairs). Oh, one last thing- they don't want you washing clothes in the room due to water restrictions in Madrid- but they do have laundry facilities on site (for a fee, of course).So- if you're not overweight/too tall, have light luggage and earplugs, you'll be fine. A good deal for the price. 
