<Author>freyas_dad
<Content>I liked it! OK, reviews are by their very nature subjective but this small hostal is obviously doing something right as it seems to be always in tripadvisor's top 5 madrid hotels.although i visit spain regularly, i hadn't been to madrid before so wasn't sure how the barrera would compare against the other-much higher rated-places i have stayed at in iberia, however at the end of my stay i was pleased with my choice.i shalln't add a great deal to what has already been said;the hostal doesn't do food, it is well situated in a fairly central area, and is on a busyish road.yes on first sight it looks a little unsalubrious, but almost directly opposite is a 4 star hotel, and just down the road is another 4 star place so the area is actually fine.i didn't find the traffic noise a problem, although i was on a room that was on a side street there was some little background traffic noise but this didn't interfere with my sleep at all.what i would point out is that if you are planning on some bedroom action it may be worth giving this hostal a miss as the walls don't stop much in the soundproofing department, so any honeymooners would probably do well to go somewhere else!i stayed in a twin room-it was with my father-and although the room was fairly small it had been fairly recently decorated and the bathroom, again a little compact was also fairly newly done.the room was impeccably clean on arrival and was also cleaned well during my stay.however, what made this such an enjoyable experience was the absolutely delightful Nieves, the young lady on reception and who's family appears to own the hostal. her cheerful disposition and helpful manner was a credit to her and i felt you could ask her anything and not only would she be willing to help you but would have taken you to where you wanted to go if you asked!so whilst the amenities are a little basic the friendliness and eagerness of this young woman make the hostal barrera an ideal place to spend a few days in spain's capital. 
